<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>The <strong>best pinot noir</strong> wines offer exceptional aging potential when properly cellared, though their evolution differs dramatically from more tannic varieties like Cabernet Sauvignon.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Quality Level</h3>
<p>Premier and Grand Cru Burgundies can age gracefully for <strong>15-25 years</strong>, with legendary producers like Domaine de la Romanée-Conti showing remarkable longevity. Top-tier Oregon pinots from Willamette Valley's finest sites typically peak at <strong>10-15 years</strong>, while exceptional Carneros and Russian River examples can develop beautifully for <strong>8-12 years</strong>. Entry-level pinots should be consumed within <strong>3-5 years</strong> to preserve their vibrant fruit character.</p>

<h3>Evolution and Peak Windows</h3>
<p>Young pinot noir displays bright red fruit flavors—cherry, raspberry, and strawberry—with firm acidity and subtle tannins. During aging, these primary fruits evolve into complex secondary notes of <strong>forest floor, dried herbs, and game</strong>. The wine's silky texture becomes even more refined as proteins polymerize and settle. Most premium pinots hit their stride between <strong>years 5-10</strong>, when fruit concentration balances perfectly with earthy complexity.</p>

<h3>Proper Storage Requirements</h3>
<p>Store bottles horizontally at <strong>55°F (13°C)</strong> with 60-70% humidity in complete darkness. Pinot noir's delicate structure makes it particularly sensitive to temperature fluctuations—even small variations can accelerate unwanted oxidation. Avoid vibration and strong odors, as pinot's thin skins offer less protection than thicker-skinned varieties.</p>

<h3>Recognizing Proper Aging</h3>
<p>Well-aged pinot noir develops <strong>brick-orange rim coloration</strong> while maintaining a ruby core. Aromas become more complex, showing leather, mushroom, and sous-bois characteristics alongside evolved fruit. Signs of spoilage include excessive browning throughout the wine, vinegar-like aromas, or complete loss of fruit character—indicating oxidation or cork failure.</p>

