<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Burgundy Pinot Noir and Oregon Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Burgundy Pinot Noir tends to be more earthy and mineral-driven with higher acidity, showcasing terroir through limestone soils and cool climate conditions. Oregon Pinot Noir is typically more fruit-forward with darker berry flavors, softer tannins, and a rounder mouthfeel, though top producers like Domaine Drouhin Oregon bridge both styles beautifully.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Pinot Noir good for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, Pinot Noir is excellent for beginners due to its lighter body, lower tannins, and approachable fruit flavors compared to Cabernet Sauvignon or Syrah. Start with New World examples from California's Central Coast or New Zealand's Central Otago, which offer clear fruit expression and food-friendly acidity. The grape's transparency and food versatility make it ideal for developing your palate.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How can I identify a high-quality Pinot Noir without breaking the bank?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for producers who own their vineyards rather than négociant bottlings, seek out lesser-known appellations like Sta. Rita Hills or Willamette Valley sub-AVAs, and focus on vintages 3-5 years old when prices have stabilized. Quality indicators include specific vineyard designations, sustainable farming mentions, and producers with winemaking pedigree in Pinot Noir rather than multiple varietals.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What temperature should I serve Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve Pinot Noir at 60-65°F (15-18°C), which is cooler than most people serve red wines. This temperature preserves the wine's delicate aromatics and prevents the alcohol from overwhelming the subtle fruit and earthy notes. If your bottle feels warm to the touch, refrigerate it for 20-30 minutes before serving.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Why is some Pinot Noir so expensive compared to other red wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Pinot Noir's thin skin produces lower yields per vine, and the grape requires specific cool-climate conditions with precise winemaking techniques. Premium regions like Burgundy have limited vineyard space with centuries of established hierarchy, driving up land costs. Additionally, Pinot Noir's sensitivity to vintage variation and its reputation as a "heartbreak grape" means successful producers can command premium prices.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the biggest mistakes people make when buying Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is choosing based on price alone rather than understanding regional styles and producer reputation. Many people also buy Pinot Noir too young from premium regions or store it improperly in warm conditions, which destroys its delicate structure. Additionally, expecting all Pinot Noir to taste similar leads to disappointment—the grape expresses terroir more dramatically than almost any other variety.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">If I love Pinot Noir, what other wines should I try?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Explore Nebbiolo from Italy's Piedmont region for similar elegance with more structure, or try Gamay from Beaujolais for lighter, more playful fruit character. Sangiovese from Tuscany offers comparable food-friendliness with Italian flair, while cool-climate Syrah from Northern Rhône provides more complexity while maintaining Pinot's finesse. These varieties share Pinot Noir's emphasis on terroir expression and food compatibility.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can I age the best Pinot Noir wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Top-tier Burgundy and premium American Pinot Noir can age 10-20 years or more, developing complex tertiary aromas of forest floor, leather, and dried flowers. However, most Pinot Noir is best consumed within 5-8 years of vintage to preserve its primary fruit character. The key is understanding that Pinot Noir ages differently than Cabernet—it becomes more ethereal and delicate rather than more powerful.</p>
